      • discard

        protected void discard​(HttpURLConnection conn)
                throws IOException
        Reads the input stream and error stream, but discards all data collected. This is necessary to make the connection available for further requests using HTTP keep-alives.
        Parameters:

        Throws:

      • parseRequest

        protected <R> R parseRequest​(HttpURLConnection conn,
                             AbstractResolver.InputStreamAction<R> consumer)
                      throws IOException
        Consume input stream and discards every data in error stream if available. In order that HTTP connections can be re-used (keep-alive), all output streams should be fully written and closed as well as all input streams fully consumed and closed (URLConnection.getInputStream() and HttpURLConnection.getErrorStream()).

        By default, Java will consume part of the input stream if not fully read, but it doesn't apply to error streams and the connection still have to be closed nevertheless. Furthermore, a connection implicitly opened by HttpURLConnection.getResponseCode() or URLConnection.getOutputStream()} should also be consumed and closed by this.

        Type Parameters:
        R - return type of the consumer
        Parameters:
        conn - http connection
        consumer - consumer that should fully read the input
        Returns:
        return value of the consumer
        Throws:
        IOException - on reading the original input stream
        See Also:
        Peristent Connections
